<TEXT>
fire on a ship an enclosed space made 
primarily of heatconducting metal can turn into a nightmare for 
seamen trying to extinguish the blaze experts say 
the latest example came when fire broke out on the uss white 
plains killing six people and injuring five the blaze on the navy 
supply ship in the south china sea was apparently caused by a fuel 
leak officials said tuesday 
guy colonna a marine specialist with the national fire 
protection association a quincy mass organization that works to 
develop fire protection standards said a major problem confronting 
firefighters aboard a ship is restrictions on the use of water 
the way to fight fire is with water obviously at sea you 
cant add too much or you sink the vessel or impair its 
stability he said you cant pour water on it the way you 
would on land 
maj dave neudorfer who works in the navys safety and 
survivability division said water used to dampen a blaze has to be 
pumped off the ship to keep the vessel afloat 
another hazard is intense heat that builds up on a ship with 
temperatures often reaching 3000 degrees farhenheit metal 
conducts heat rapidly and an allmetal facility is not like a 
building where you have cement walls colonna said 
a navy source speaking on condition of anonymity said the heat 
on the white plains was so hot sailors were limited to fiveminute 
stints in fighting the blaze 
additionally ships are compartmentalized frequently making it 
difficult to move equipment from deck to deck colonna said an 
explosion that ripped through the no 2 gun turret of the uss iowa 
last month was contained to that area fortyseven men were killed 
colonna who was formerly in the coast guard said the navy 
trains all sailors in firefighting techniques but special 
casualty control teams spring into action when fire breaks out 
even so neudorfer said ontheground training is a 
kindergarten situation compared to a shipboard fire which 
often produces billowing smoke and toxic fumes from material used 
to coat electrical cables and insulate equipment 
repair lockers containing hoses and breathing equipment are 
normally kept at each end of the ship colonna said in a large 
ship like an aircraft carrier equipment bins are located at 
various places 
but fire affects everyone one board because it can disable a 
ships navigation and steering equipment and electricity he said 
when they have a fire its almost like a military operation 
he said its a nightmare things are going on and people have 
their jobs to do 
the navy meantime is continually trying to upgrade its ability 
to cope with fires particularly using new technologies neudorfer 
said 
were challenging the technical world to come up with fire 
resistant coating on electrical cables he said 
moreover the navy is looking at socalled sticky water that 
does not evaporate when it is doused on a fire 
on a practical level the navy recently introduced special 
firefighting coveralls for sailors and is looking at 
manufacturing taller boots 
what they found on the uss stark was that water was coming 
over the boots and burning their feet neudorfer said 
thirtyseven sailors were killed when the stark was hit by a 
iraqi missile in the persian gulf in may 1987 crew members 
battled for 24 hours to bring under control the fires set off by 
the attack 
</TEXT>
