<DOCNO> AP890510-0024 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations emergency stockpile of oil is 
losing its value as a shield against an energy crisis former 
energy secretary james schlesinger told congress 
schlesinger told a house banking subcommittee tuesday that the 
strategic petroleum reserve was being undermined by the nations 
growing appetite for imported oil 
as a protective device it offers less and less protection 
schlesinger said 
although the government is continuing to fill the oil reserve 
imports are growing even faster as a result the reserves would 
not stretch as far in an emergency as they would have just a few 
years ago he said 
the salt caverns in louisiana and texas that hold about 565 
million barrels of government crude oil could replace about 70 days 
of imports at the current import rate of 8 million barrels a day 
four years ago the oil reserve was equal to 115 days of imports 
it is particularly distressing to me that this principle 
bulwark is being undermined schlesinger said adding that 
national security is weakened as the united states grows more 
vulnerable to a cutoff of oil imports 
coincidentally energy secretary james d watkins was touring a 
strategic petroleum reserve storage site in louisiana on tuesday to 
watch a test of the system that would be used in an actual 
emergency to pump the oil out of the caverns 
the reserve which was started in 1975 in response to the arab 
oil embargo has never been used 
the united states currently relies on imports for about 44 
percent of its supplies and the energy department has projected 
the rate will reach at least 65 percent by the turn of the century 
the highest rate in us history was 46 percent in 1977 
schlesinger said the country was likely to face an even greater 
reliance on foreign oil in the 1990s as domestic oil production 
continues to decline and consumption grows 
robert w fri president of resources for the future an 
independent research institute told the subcommittee congress 
should increase the target level of the strategic petroleum reserve 
to 1 billion barrels the target under existing legislation is 750 
million barrels which is expected to be reached in 1995 
the energy department said last month in a report prepared for 
congress that it would take more than 6 billion and at least 10 
years to expand the reserve to 1 billion barrels the cost estimate 
was based on the current price of imported oil 
the report did not take a position on whether the reserve should 
be expanded but said an interagency group was making a detailed 
analysis of the costs and benefits of expansion the groups 
recommendations are due later this year 
</TEXT>
