<TEXT>
a group of chinese economists is backing a 
radical proposal to use chinese labor and japanese capital to 
develop the soviet far east the worlds largest untapped 
depository of natural resources 
the ministry of agriculture meanwhile is considering a 
massive cooperation program with the soviet union to grow crops 
and process food in chinas northeast 
the proposals represent a new vision of sovietchinese economic 
relations which now consist mainly of exchanging lowquality 
russian wood and iron ore for chinese thermoses and canned foods 
both plans were formulated earlier this year as china and soviet 
officials haggled over the countries first summit in 30 years 
president mikhail s gorbachev will come to china on may 15 
accompanied by trade representatives ready to discuss economic 
relations 
the proposals stem from a realization that the current barter 
and border trade has its limits 
ten years ago there was little trade between the countries last 
year they signed contracts for about 325 billion in goods but 
because of transportation bottlenecks 25 percent of the soviet 
goods and 40 percent of the chinese products were not delivered 
thousands of tons of goods also were returned because they were 
shoddy 
theres lots of hoopla about recordsetting trade figures and 
contracts but theres little future in that said fan yueqiang 
head of the institute of development studies a think tank in 
beijing 
we only sell each other things we cant sell for foreign 
exchange he said they send us lowquality wood and we send 
them secondclass canned food 
fan and his deputy han xiaofeng believe the future of 
chinesesoviet trade is in combining soviet technical skill and 
natural resources with chinese labor and capital from third 
countries such as japan and south korea 
labor export began last year when more than 100 chinese 
