<TEXT>
legislation requiring the oil industry to 
train emergency response teams to quickly handle spills would help 
protect the entire american coastline says the new jersey 
congressman who introduced the bill 
rep jim saxton rnj proposed the clean ocean act of 1989 on 
tuesday to help mitigate the environmental hazards of oil spills 
he said he hoped to garner strong bipartisan support for the 
measure which is already backed by colleagues in california rhode 
island florida and hawaii 
the thrust of what we are doing today focuses on the entire 
american coastline saxton said at a news conference the fact 
of the matter is that an oil spill can occur anywhere anywhere 
oil is produced where it is transported and where it is refined 
saxton was named chairman in february of the republican research 
committees clean oceans task force 
eight oil refineries are located along the delaware river near 
his district last year more than threequarters of the 66 million 
tons of cargo that moved through delaware river ports were 
petroleum products he said 
saxton said his legislation would ensure that industryfunded 
emergency crews can respond within five hours to spills such as the 
march 24 accident that dumped 10 million gallons of crude oil into 
prince william sound alaska when the tanker exxon valdez ran 
aground on a reef 
that spill continues to spur legislation 
sen frank r lautenberg dnj expressing concern about the 
possibility of a major oil spill in new york harbor on monday 
announced plans to introduce a bill requiring coast guard review 
and approval of oil spill contingency plans 
the measure would hold the federal government responsible for 
determining when a cleanup was complete and would establish an oil 
spill liability fund for cleanups if private companies lacked the 
resources 
on tuesday sen ted stevens ralaska introduced a legislative 
package to create a 500 million oil spill research and restoration 
fund financed through a pennyabarrel tax on refined domestic and 
imported oil the measure also would give the coast guard the 
authority to assume immediate control of large or lifethreatening 
oil spills in prince william sound and use industry funds in 
response to a major spill 
another stevens bill would require tankers crossing the sound to 
have equipment and vessels in place in the event of a spill and to 
conduct practice drills at least twice a year his measures would 
allow oil companies to be sued in federal court if cleanup promises 
were broken 
saxtons bill requires regionally located emergency teams to be 
in place by jan 1 1991 they must be certified by the coast guard 
and subject to unannounced periodic drills 
violators face fines of 500000 to 1 million with chief 
executive officers assuming liability he said 
capt richard larrabee chief of the coast guards environmental 
response division said current federal policy holds a spiller 
responsible for timely and effective cleanup of his own spill 
in effect if the federal onscene coordinator determines that 
spiller is not acting effectively then he steps in using federal 
resources and cleans it up larrabee said 
in addition the coast guard has contingency plans in place for 
each of its approximately 48 ports 
states also may regulate the industry 
