city schools chancellor richard r green whose 
muchheralded arrival last year from minneapolis brought new hope 
to the nations biggest school system died today of asthmarelated 
causes he was 52 
the citys first black schools chancellor was brought into st 
lukesroosevelt hospital center suffering from acute respiratory 
arrest and died 40 minutes later said dr kenneth goetz the 
attending physician 
i was a great admirer of him i thought that he had the 
ability to have a major positive impact on the school system in 
the short time he was here he demonstrated that said mayor 
edward i koch 
green took over the nearly 1 millionstudent system in march 
1988 after a long and bitter selection process that pitted him 
against the favorite of the teachers union 
as an outsider from minneapolis where he served seven years as 
school superintendent and was widely credited with turning around a 
failing system green offered hope for new approaches for a school 
system plagued with a high dropout rate crumbling buildings and a 
politically combative hierarchy 
but he soon found himself contending with reports of drug abuse 
theft and sexual misconduct by teachers principals and school 
board officials in response to the scandals he suspended two 
community school boards 
critics faulted him for his lowkey approach but green 
counseled them to keep your eye on the prize and thats the 
children of the city and expect the chancellor will be the no 1 
cheerleader for them 
green was raised in minneapolis and rose through the 
schoolsystem ranks there as a teacher principal and assistant 
superintendent 
sandra feldman president of the united federation of teachers 
in new york city said of greens death i think its a terrible 
tragedy and a terrible loss for the students and staff 
flags at city schools flew at halfstaff today 
</TEXT>
