<TEXT>
the national transportation safety board says 
the crew of an eastern airlines jet was to blame when the plane 
cracked open on landing in pensacola fla in 1987 
the board in determining probable cause of the incident at a 
meeting tuesday said the captain failed to maintain a proper 
descent rate on final approach and both he and the first officer 
failed to properly monitor flight instruments 
the tail section of the plane was dragged 7000 feet down the 
runway 
three of the 105 passengers aboard the dc9 received minor 
injuries the twinengine jetliner was landing dec 27 1987 in 
rain and fog on a flight from richmond va after a stopover in 
atlanta 
board investigators noted that five other dc9s had cracked in a 
similar manner after similar hard landings that exceeded the 
planes design capabilities they said they found no signs of metal 
fatigue or corrosion in the eastern plane 
the hard landing left a twofoot crack circling the fuselage 
between the wings and the rearmounted engines 
the approach got away from the captain said board 
investigator jack drake he said the crew should have taken the 
plane around for another approach when it failed to stabilize the 
approach below 1000 feet 
the boards report did not identify the pilot or first officer 
</TEXT>
