<TEXT>
the barrage of charged particles from the sun 
may be contributing to the damage to the earths protective ozone 
layer a pair of government scientists reported wednesday 
very dramatic changes have occurred in the number of 
electrons raining down on the earth between 1979 and 1984 linwood 
callis of the national aeronautics and space administration said at 
a meeting of the american geophysical union 
this flow of electrons enhanced by the solar wind an energy 
flow from the sun leads to the formation of oxides of nitrogen in 
the upper parts of the stratosphere 
in turn those nitrogen compounds can settle into the 
stratosphere where if you have any kind of significant buildup 
then what you have is the possibility of catalytic destruction of 
ozone said callis 
ozone helps protect the earth from potentially damaging 
ultraviolet radiation from the sun 
what the model calculations show and that the data confirm is 
that from 1979 to 1985 the nitrogen oxide levels in the polar 
lower stratosphere probably increased betweeen 30 and 80 or 90 
percent in the equatorial region there have been increases much 
smaller on the order of 10 or 15 percent callis said 
damage to the ozone over the south pole has been widely 
discussed in recent years callis said that socalled antarctic 
ozone hole appears to be largely a result of chlorine compounds 
trapped over the polar areas since ice particles in this region 
tend to remove many nitrogen compounds from the air 
the interest that we have in this is primarily related to 
global ozone there are larger than expected ozone changes 
said callis 
scientists have warned that if that ozone damage were to spread 
to other parts of the earth the increased radiation could cause an 
increase in skin cancer international efforts are being made to 
reduce or ban the use of ozonedamaging chemicals 
callis and dan baker also of nasa reported that they have used 
satellite data to study levels of ozone nitrogen oxides and other 
chemicals around the world 
in the air about 16 miles above the surface the area where 
ozone is most concentrated they found the gas depleted by as much 
as 14 percent between 1979 and 1985 callis said 
this could be occurring because of some natural changes in 
atmospheric chemistry he said but having it occur at the same 
time the flood of charged particles from the sun is increasing 
makes them consider the possibility of cause and effect 
natural changes in the solar cycle should reduce the amount of 
incoming charged particles between now and the mid1990s said 
callis and he and baker are interested in seeing if ozone levels 
will recover during that period 
the flow of particles is lowest during periods of sunspot 
maximums and increased when there were fewer sunspots 
there are clear links between the state of the 
magnetosphere and the state of the middle atmosphere callis said 
</TEXT>
