<TEXT>
richard r green who became new york citys 
first black schools chancellor when he was recruited from 
minneapolis 14 months ago died unexpectedly wednesday after a 
severe asthma attack he was 52 
the death stunned city leaders and educators who had pinned 
their hopes for reform of the nations largest school system on 
green a nononsense administrator with a dogged sense of his 
mission 
green who had a history of asthma and took medicine to control 
it arrived at st lukesroosevelt hospital center at 230 am 
suffering from acute respiratory arrest the attending physician 
kenneth goetz said he died 40 minutes later 
an autopsy determined the cause of death was acute and chronic 
bronchial asthma said ellen borakove of the city medical 
examiners office 
we have suffered a great loss said mayor edward i 
koch who rushed to the hospital when he learned of greens attack 
he was starting to turn the system around he loved the 
children 
gov mario cuomo calling green an outstanding educator with 
immense potential proposed the city name a school for green to 
honor his efforts to rebuild crumbling school buildings 
disintegrating buildings were just one of the problems faced by 
green upon his arrival in new york in march 1988 his was a stormy 
tenure marked by the arrest of a principal for buying crack 
repeated episodes of guntoting in schools and corruption 
allegations against local school boards 
he embarked upon a herculean task he took over the 
leadership of our school system at a time when many were gloomy 
even cynical about its prospects said manhattan borough 
president david dinkins 
green had made a start he cut the central school board 
bureaucracy by onefifth won friends and allies among teachers and 
was applauded for his personal touch when dealing with students 
richard green related to teachers as a colleague and to 
students as a teacher said sandra feldman president of the 
united federation of teachers 
at an emergency meeting wednesday afternoon the board of 
education approved deputy chancellor bernard mecklowitz as acting 
chancellor wagner said the search committee that chose green will 
be asked to find his permanent successor 
the arkansasborn green was a product of the minneapolis school 
system and rose through its ranks as a teacher principal and 
assistant superintendent before becoming its first black 
superintendent in july 1980 
while he received credit for turning the system around two of 
his policies stirred controversy using test gates for 
promotion from kindergarten and school centralization to help 
promote desegregation 
during his eight years in minneapolis he was mentioned as a 
candidate to run the school systems in houston san francisco and 
seattle new york tapped him after months of infighting by 
politicians union heads and other leaders 
while green was hailed as the best of three finalists when he 
received the job race was an issue in his selection with blacks 
making up 38 percent of the citys 939000 students there was 
pressure for a black candidate to receive the job 
green is survived by his wife gwen and four children a 
memorial service is scheduled friday flags at city schools will 
fly at halfstaff for 30 days said board of education spokesman 
robert terte 
