<TEXT>
the progovernment teachers union and its 
dissident wing reached an agreement on wages and union corruption 
wednesday night ending a 3weekold strike 
the national education workers federation agreed with the 
dissident democratic coordinate to accept a government offer of a 
25 percent increase in wages and benefits and to adopt 
anticorruption measures inside the union a union official said on 
condition of anonymity 
about 8000 teachers voted wednesday night and approved the 
agreement overwhelmingly the official said he did not have a vote 
count and did not say why so few voted 
there is agreement between both factions to end the strike 
the official said classes will be open tomorrow thursday 
the education department also said it would replace the 
superintendents in all 14 of the nations districts it said the 
move was designed to increase efficiency but gave no details 
the democratic coordinate which claims the loyalty of about 
half the federations 11 million members struck april 17 to 
demand a 100 percent increase in pay and democratic reforms within 
the union 
the strike closed roughly half of the nations grammar and high 
schools and vocational institutes 
the teachers whose takehome pay averaged 147 a month 
rejected a first government offer of a 15 percent increase the 
government later raised it to 25 percent effective may 15 
the strike also led to the ouster of carlos jonguitud barrios 
an oldstyle machine politician close to the governing 
institutional revolutionary party 
jonguitud and a group of corrupt cronies had controlled the 
union for 17 years 
union dissidents accused jonguitud of mismanaging union funds 
and keeping his group in power by forbidding rankandfile 
assemblies and rigging union elections 
jonguituds replacement by elba esther gordillo a moderate 
loyal to the ruling party removed a major stumbling block in the 
negotiations between the two sides coordinate leader teodoro 
palomino refused to talk with jonguitud but said he could deal with 
gordillo 
the two sides also agreed to set up a bilateral commission to 
negotiate wage increases for about 300000 school janitors and 
nonteaching staff by july 15 
