<TEXT>
will a fleet of foreign container ships sidle up 
to docks in major us ports some dark day in the future and 
proceed to load aboard all the assets foreigners have purchased 
only in a nightmare could it happen but that image symbolizes 
the horror that americans often feel that foreigners eager to own 
american investments are buying us out of house home and country 
it isnt quite so even though the united states is in a 
negative position in regard to international investments with 
foreigners investing roughly 370 billion more in this country than 
americans invest abroad 
and yes it is true that if foreigners en masse buy or sell 
american assets they could indeed disrupt segments of the american 
economy raising or lowering prices precipitously 
but some assurances are in order 
1 foreigners can only load financial paper not physical 
assets onto those imaginary ships but why should they by cashing 
in their chips they would be foresaking investments in the worlds 
biggest single marketplace 
2 some of the big figures that are tossed about arent for 
many practical purposes what they seem to be 
when for example j paul getty left the united states for 
residence in britain he caused a big drop in the officialy reported 
us investment position but getty took not a dime with him when 
he relocated 
that latter example is used by robert brown tax foundation 
president to make a point the negative investment position of the 
united states may be no reason to cheer but it is no reason to 
grind teeth either 
brown points out that while foreign investment in the united 
states exceeds 15 trillion the united states is no slouch in 
foreign investments with total us assets abroad amounting to 
around 12 trillion 
that he suggests is what the global economy is all about and 
that to suggest a perfect balance of investments is unrealistic 
foreigners invest in the united states he says because it is a 
desirable place in which to invest he points to a strong economy 
stable politics dynamic private sector and a labor force that can 
produce with the best 
why shouldnt they want to invest in such a market 
still he suggests that isnt the reason why foreigners invest 
more here than we do there the real reason he says is that us 
tax policy discourages americans from saving that is investing 
in their own country 
what this country needs in order to correct the imbalance of 
investments says brown are incentives for savings and investments 
and a tax policy that aids rather than damages the competitive 
position of us companies 
in that respect he places himself among a growing list of 
critics of us taxing practice which penalizes those who risk 
capital imposes taxes on those who save and provides tax breaks 
for being in debt 
change the tax situation he suggests and americans might 
recognize what foreigners see in the us economy a superior 
investment opportunity 
