<TEXT>
pedro rodriguez fondly remembers the fun he 
had as a kid watching mexican plays and feature films at the 
guadalupe theater which in its heyday during the 1940s and 50s 
served as the anchor for mexican art and entertainment in the city 
today rodriguez still has fun as executive director of the 
guadalupe cultural arts center a nonprofit organization that not 
only runs the restored 410seat theater but sponsors literary 
theatrical musical dance painting and visual arts workshops and 
shows to preserve mexican culture 
with grants from the city and federal governments and 
corporations the center already has the nations largest 
curriculum devoted to development and preservation of mexican 
cultural arts and operates on a 1 million annual budget 
were it not for the fact that the mexican culture itself is 
very strong here the cultural arts would not have survived but it 
just barely did and i think the creation of this institution is 
very timely said rodriguez a former university professor who 
took over the guadalupe cultural arts center in 1983 a year after 
it was formed 
now we have hundreds of artists yearly that we support 
directly through contracts and through the training that we provide 
for about 900 students per year and the art and cultural events 
throughout the community 
but the center hopes to preserve more than just cultural arts 
it also hopes to improve the areas social and economic environment 
the center and the avenida guadalupe development association a 
nonprofit economic development agency are transforming a 
threeblock area around the guadalupe theater from a dilapidated 
barrio dominated by bars and shacks to a medical retail and 
entertainment showplace that will serve one of the citys oldest 
hispanic neighborhoods 
i think all this construction and all the changes are going to 
help everyone here said 48yearold roger mercado a lifelong 
resident of the guadalupe area i think all the art coming out of 
here also will help us communicate with the rest of the community 
the guadalupe theater opened in the 1939 served as host for 
hundreds of spanishlanguage plays and movie premieres until it 
fell into disrepair in the early 70s in 1979 performing and 
visual arts groups banded together to better secure funding for 
hispanic arts by 1982 the group was known as the guadalupe 
cultural arts center a year later the city provided 1 million 
for renovation of the guadalupe theater which by then was being 
used as a flea market 
rodriguez said the centers 17member staff has had to use all 
types of marketing techniques to attract not only those in the 
neighborhood but many nonhispanics who are weary of traveling to 
an area surrounded by housing projects 
there is a certain image about coming to this side of town 
that we have to get people past and that was that it was not safe 
to come over here but thats not true once they get over here we 
know we have them hooked and i think everyone in the community is 
pretty proud of what is happening here rodriquez said 
the guadalupe theater now holds art exhibitions in its foyer 
gallery brings in foreign and artistic films and is home to the 
san antonio cinefestival a hispanic film festival in its 13th 
year its other major event is the tejano conjunto festival a 
fourday event now in its eighth year which will bring in hundreds 
of artists and thousands of spectators to hear accordianplaying 
musicians 
the theater also is home to the theatre arts program which 
produces up to four bilingual plays a year through its resident 
company los actores de san antonio the actors of san antonio 
the centers visual arts program annually sponsors about nine 
exhibits with emphasis on hispanic and native american artists in 
the summer it provides a free weekly outdoor film festival in 
guadalupe plaza 
the centers literature program offers poetry and fiction 
readings and annually sponsors a bookfair this years major 
presenters are pulitzer prize winner alice walker the color 
purple and mexican poet octavio paz 
classes for adults and children are offered in all the various 
arts programs at the center and 15 other locations across the city 
we work out of very makeshift kinds of situations the only 
thing that we do have that is firstrate is the theater but 
everything else that we do we do on a shoestring and in poor 
conditions rodriguez said 
but our vision centers around the creation of an institution 
that will be anchored in bedrock here to stay forever to provide 
services so the mexican arts culture continues to subsist and 
flourish 
there are plans for a 50000squarefoot classroom and office 
building next to the theater rodriquez also envisions use of the 
former progreso theater across the street from the guadalupe as a 
rehearsal and reception hall 
those developments would add to area renovations by the 
development association which built guadalupe plaza and plans to 
open a 48stall mexican market later this spring a private drug 
store and medical complex already are operating next to the plaza 
the avenida guadalupe development association has spent 75 
million in the past decade renovating three city blocks surrounding 
the guadalupe theater 
this neighborhood was one of the pride and joys of san 
antonio but because of demographic and social changes it began to 
deteriorate in the 1960s and 70s said david garza executive 
director of the development agency 
we are just trying to revitalize the area and change the 
conditions of the neighorhood to attract the businesses and the 
families or otherwise we are going to see this neighborhood die 
away garza said 
