students against drunken driving chapters are active at radcliff 
middle school and north hardin high school linda probus a 
counselor hired to help students cope with the tragedy said 
drinking and driving is no longer acceptable behavior among the 
students 
residents take time to pull off the road to report suspected 
drunken drivers said police officer greg mayfield 
on the anniversary of the crash radcliff is holding a memorial 
expected to draw hundreds of people 
many of those touched by the crash have mixed emotions about the 
ceremony 
i think the community not to forget the families is ready to 
put the accident to rest said dick booher whose son jason 
escaped from the bus 
we want to be left alone we want to try to put our lives back 
together said williams a career soldier who spends much of his 
offduty time speaking publicly about the dangers of drunken 
driving 
but another reminder of the tragedy will come nov 8 when 
mahoney goes on trial his role is still a troubling one for many 
involved 
ms probus said many of the students who survived the crash have 
changed their attitudes toward mahoney initially they really 
really wanted mahoney to die as they have come to grips with the 
tragedy they want him punished left in jail but not to be 
killed 
the memorial sunday will mark a milepost in this tragedy but 
will not end it legislators still will debate tougher laws state 
agencies will weigh the benefits of additional training for school 
bus drivers against the cost drunken drivers still will kill 
innocent victims 
first sgt lee williams still will think of his family when he 
sees a bus and he will continue to warn people of the danger 
i give these speeches for the robins and the kristens who 
havent been killed i give these speeches for the husbands and the 
wives who havent been hurt 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

