<DOCNO> AP890510-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
doctors have found a new way to augment their 
income the sale of prescription drugs but the trend has raised 
the issue of conflict of interest with some questioning the 
propriety of doctors profiting from drugs they prescribe in the 
third article in a continuing series the business of medicine 
science writer daniel q haney and national writer fred bayles 
report on the debate over doctors selling drugs the next story in 
the series will look at the growing business that supplies the 
drugs to the doctors 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when family doctors pull out their 
prescription pads they often have a new question for patients do 
you pay for your own medicine 
if they do says dr john garofalo i tell them you can 
purchase your medications here 
doctors are going into the drug business while these physicians 
contend it is good for patients others believe this venture is a 
clear conflict of interest for it can give physicians a financial 
reason to write unnecessary prescriptions 
accurate figures are elusive but experts estimate that perhaps 
8 percent of the 330000 officebased physicians have miniature 
pharmacies on hand 
the business is fast and simple the doctor reaches into a 
cabinet pulls out a singleprescription bottle of antibiotics or 
decongestant fills out the label and sells the medicine on the 
spot usually for about the same price as the neighborhood 
drugstore 
not everyone can buy from their doctors many insurers dont pay 
for physiciansold drugs and most doctors dont accept insurance 
cards but if patients pay their own pill bills they almost always 
buy from their doctors 
those who branch into this new sideline find it easy to justify 
the patient likes the convenience and the doctor can often clear 
10000 or more a year with little extra work 
we dont sniff at the profit said dr edward saltzman but 
its not the path to riches 
while his 12member pediatrics group in suburban miami clears 
70000 to 80000 a year on medicines saltzman views drug sales 
primarily as a marketing tool to build patient loyalty its 
another way of bonding them to us he said 
in most of the country doctors can routinely sell medicine with 
minimal regulation only seven states arkansas massachusetts 
montana nebraska oklahoma texas and utah make it difficult or 
impossible 
the doctors buy their pills from wholesalers called repackagers 
this industry in existence barely a decade puts medicines in 
patientsize bottles and supplies them to doctors along with 
suggested price lists peeloff labels and charts for easy 
recordkeeping 
some are concerned this venture could erode medicines ethical 
underpinnings they worry that doctors might write prescriptions to 
get the 3 profit they make on each one not because sick people 
need them while most doctors undoubtedly are honest the ethicists 
fear physician dispensing as its called will undermine patients 
faith in their doctors 
what matters is whether there is a potential conflict of 
interest and whether this is perceived by patients and therefore 
undermines trust said daniel wikler a university of wisconsin 
bioethicist 
those who dislike the practice cite several potential abuses 
doctors might prescribe only the 20 or 30 medications they keep 
in their offices even though these may not be the best ones in 
particular situations 
patients might feel pressured to buy medicine from their 
doctors for fear of offending them 
doctors might concentrate on drugs with the highest profit 
margins or prescribe unnecessarily to make more money 
at least some doctors do bend to such enticements in the last 
three years about 15 states have taken disciplinary action against 
doctors for dispensing abuses according to a recent survey by the 
inspector generals office of the us department of health and 
human services among the most common problems was overprescribing 
while dispensing doctors say they would never compromise their 
integrity they do agree they view dispensing as one element of a 
more important question economic survival they are squeezed on 
one side by cutrate fees from medicare and medicaid on the other 
by competition from health maintenance organizations and other 
doctors 
with the way things are going especially in primary care we 
have to keep trying to think of more and more ways to make a 
dollar said garofalo a 35yearold family practitioner here in 
maines capital 
garofalo started filling presriptions three years ago two of 
the other three family practices in the city have followed his lead 
now garofalo and two associates net 5000 to 10000 a year on 
medicines while this might be small potatoes to a heart surgeon 
doctors on the front lines of primary care are less grandly paid 
in maine for instance family practitioners average 54000 a year 
you cant survive in medicine these days if you dont let the 
business part influence some of what you do said garofalo 
physicians are not distributed evenly throughout the country or 
across specialties and many places have too many doctors there 
simply are not enough patients to go around so to some doctors 
selling medicine is a tactic that sets them apart from the 
competition so they can attract and hold patients 
its a good service for the patient said dr norman 
glanzman a family practitioner in carmel ind people often come 
in coughing and feeling ill the last thing they want to do is wait 
around at a drugstore 
but dr norman fost head of the ethics committee of the 
american academy of pediatrics believes it is wrong for doctors to 
sell medicines for profit because this may influence their 
prescribing habits 
as it says in the bible where your treasure is there your 
heart will be he said 
several major doctor organizations including fosts 
pediatricians and the american academy of family physicians have 
official policies that uphold physicians right to dispense 
the american medical associations council on ethical and 
judicial affairs came out against regular dispensing because of its 
appearance of impropriety but the amas house of delegates 
later voted in favor of physicians right to dispense drugs when 
it is in the best interest of the patient 
we make countless decisions regarding how long a patient stays 
in the hospital whether he comes back for a revisit how often to 
do laboratory studies said dr daniel w shea a green bay 
wis pediatrician i think that for the practicing physician 
life is one continuum of conflict of interest but you must put the 
the best interest of the patient first 
despite such sentiment and support from various medical 
associations individual doctors such as family practitioner dudley 
phillips of darlington md find the trend unappealing ive 
always felt i might get too interested in selling drugs and not 
taking care of people he said 
and pediatrician william bartholome of the university of kansas 
said any patient walking out of a doctors office with five bottles 
of medicine should ask himself 
are these the drugs i needed or were these the drugs that had 
the best profit margin and that the doc just happened to have on 
hand did i need all five of them or did i get them because my 
doctor needs a new car 
</TEXT>
