<TEXT>
karl brunner an influential economist 
and leading exponent of monetarism has died after a long bout with 
a spinal tumor 
brunner who died tuesday was 73 
many economists credited the swissborn economist and other top 
monetarists with steering the federal reserve system toward tight 
controls on the money supply in the early 1980s helping to halt 
the inflation of the late 1970s 
monetarists believe governments only important role in the 
economy is to regulate the money supply through a slow but steady 
growth rate 
karl brunner was a much valued leader of the intellectual 
community in economics with a truly international network of 
academics policy makers and business leaders as colleagues said 
paul w macavoy dean of the university of rochesters william e 
simon graduate school of business administration brunner had 
taught at rochester since 1971 
prime minister margaret thatcher of britain regularly sought his 
counsel and switzerland and sweden used his advice to manage their 
economies 
brunner grew up in switzerland the son of an astronomy 
professor at the university of zurich he studied history there 
after graduating from high school and became fascinated by 
economics 
his studies were interrupted by world war ii he served as a 
lieutenant in the swiss army 
brunner received his doctorate in economics from zurich in 1943 
and worked at the swiss national bank until 1949 when he studied 
at harvard university and the university of chicago on a 
rockefeller fellowship 
he taught at several universities before coming to rochester 
and held a joint professorship at rochester and the university of 
bern in switzerland for most of his career 
brunners wife rosmarie died in 1986 he is survived by nieces 
and nephews in europe a memorial service will be held in rochester 
on saturday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

