<TEXT>
viacom inc charging that time inc and its 
cable television units are monopolizing paytv has filed a 24 
billion antitrust lawsuit seeking to loosen times grip on the 
cable industry 
viacom parent of the showtime cable television channel filed 
its suit against time and its home box office and other cable tv 
divisions in us district court in manhattan 
viacom charged time and its tv holdings are monopolizing 
conspiring to monopolize and attempting to restrain trade 
practices prohibited by the federal sherman and clayton antitrust 
acts 
the suit contended the violations entitle viacom to recover 
three times the actual monetary damage done to it an amount placed 
at 800 million after trebling the amount sought in damages is 
24 billion 
time blasted viacoms suit as baseless 
many of the allegations rehash issues that have been 
periodically raised for more than a decade stated time one of 
the worlds largest entertainment and publishing conglomerates 
on several occasions the justice department has reviewed many if 
not all of these allegations and repeatedly concluded that no 
action was warranted 
viacom alleged that time and its home box office inc american 
television and communications corp and manhattan cable television 
inc are engaging in an integrated series of predatory and 
exclusionary acts and strategies designed to increase the costs of 
their rivals raise barriers to entry and expansion and otherwise 
entrench themselves as monopolists by anticompetitive conduct 
injuring the competitive process and ultimately consumers the 
suit said 
among the numerous complaints listed viacom said hbo abuses its 
position as the dominant firm in the business of providing pay tv 
programming services 
hbo holds about 65 percent of the nationwide market for these 
services a market share three times larger than its closest rival 
the suit said 
these programming services are competing for access to national 
and local markets hbos dominance allows it to undercut 
competitions prices to such an extent that competitors never 
obtain a large enough subscriber base to survive viacom alleged 
viacom also asked the court to bar time and its pay tv operators 
from further allegedly anticompetitive behavior 
time vice president for corporate communications louis j 
slovinsky said viacoms showtime unit actually engages in some of 
the practices that it has criticized hbo about in the suit for 
instance both hbo and showtime have negotiated exclusive contracts 
with studios for films according to slovinsky 
also he said time is puzzled why viacom has decided to launch 
the legal salvo at this point 
this is the kind of suit they could have brought any time in 
the past 10 years why are they doing it now slovinsky said 
he noted that the issues specified in the suit have been 
examined thoroughly most recently they were addressed when the 
government reviewed the antitrust implications of the proposed 18 
billion merger between time and warner communications inc he said 
a completed merger would make time warner the worlds largest 
media concern with projected annual revenue of 10 billion and in 
all likelihood increase the combined companys clout in every field 
in which it operates 
viacom said that more than a year was spent preparing the legal 
action against time indicating it was not prompted by the 
timewarner merger announcement in march 
slovinsky said time will contest the many charges viacom has 
leveled and he predicted vindication 
this is a suit that includes the kitchen sink and the coffee 
grounds he said 
</TEXT>
