<TEXT>
shareholders of texaco inc have approved a new 
poison pill to protect the oil company from unwanted takeover 
attempts 
the poison pill also known as a shareholder rights plan was 
one of several companybacked measures approved tuesday at the 
texaco annual meeting three proposals opposed by the texaco board 
two urging the company to curtail its operations in south africa 
and one to make proxy votes confidential were rejected 
a shareholder vote on a poison pill is rare but texaco agreed 
to the vote after shareholders handed the company a victory in a 
proxy fight a year ago with takeover strategist carl icahn 
the pill had been a point of contention between texaco and 
icahn its largest stockholder until they settled their 
differences aside in late january 
the antitakeover plan entitles stockholders to buy additional 
shares of common stock at a considerable discount within 10 days of 
the announcement that a suitor had acquired 20 percent or more of 
texaco common stock without meeting certain conditions 
the plans intent is to dilute the value of the suitors 
interest and increase the cost of making the offer 
the texaco plan however would not be triggered if an offer for 
the company was considered by the board of directors to be a bona 
fide fully financed allcash offer and meets other conditions 
the takeover offer also would have to give the board reasonable 
time to explore other opportunities 
the plan was approved tuesday by 842 percent of the shares 
voting said texaco spokeswoman anita larsen texaco has 250 
million shares of common stock outstanding 
other proposals approved by shareholders included two special 
dividends worth about 2 billion an employee compensation plan 
tied to performance the hiring of a new auditor and the election 
of five directors 
the meeting tuesday marked the first time officials of the white 
plains nybased company faced the shareholders since texaco 
launched its postbankruptcy restructuring 
texaco the nations thirdlargest oil company asked a federal 
bankruptcy court in 1987 to protect it from claims by its 
creditors the move followed a 103 billion judgment won against 
texaco by pennzoil co which charged texaco with blocking 
pennzoils plans to acquire getty oil co 
texaco emerged from bankruptcy protection last year and launched 
a restructuring program that included the projected sale of more 
than 5 billion in operating assets in february the company 
completed the sale of texaco canada inc to imperial oil ltd for 
324 billion 
after several years of some very special challenges a new 
texaco has emerged a company with its own vision for greatness a 
company with its sights set firmly on the future texaco chairman 
alfred c decrane told the shareholders tuesday 
decrane and james w kinnear texacos president and chief 
executive officer served up large helpings of optimism for the 
attentive if lowkey gathering 
the officials said the company is in good financial health and 
is poised to reclaim its position as an industry leader noting the 
recent exxon valdez oil spill in alaska kinnear also stressed that 
texaco is committed to preventing another environmental disaster 
</TEXT>
