<DOCNO> AP890510-0292 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said 
wednesday that a decision may be made soon on future use of a 
controversial program that subsidizes farm exports 
low us wheat stocks uncertainty over the 1989 crop and 
more competitive us prices in the world wheat market suggest a 
period of more cautious use of the export enhancement program 
yeutter told the house agriculture committee 
he said after the hearing that a review of the program by his 
department and the presidents office of management and budget is 
on a fast track 
he said the department has already done much of its work in the 
review and omb also is working promptly 
congressmen have criticized the bush administration for slowing 
down use of the program which discounts us farm products for 
foreign buyers other countries heavily subsidize their exports and 
the united states has used the eep as a way to compete with them 
yeutter said the administration is concerned about the wisdom of 
using eep on wheat exports in the wake of last years devastating 
drought which drastically cut domestic supplies 
last week president bush approved sale to the soviets of 15 
million metric tons of wheat under the enhancement program it was 
the first use of eep since late february but some members of 
congress said the soviets actually wanted more wheat and should 
have been sold it 
the administration also is considering selling 500000 tons of 
soybean oil to the soviets at subsidized prices the washington 
post reported in thursdays editions 
the subsidy would cost taxpayers about 75 million at todays 
prices the post said 
the eep is a bonus program through which us exporters are 
given extra commodities to enhance the amount they sell thereby 
bringing down the price to the buyer the bonus comes from stored 
commodities that were bought up by the government through other 
farm price support programs 
rep harold volkmer dmo asked yeutter if failure to 
aggressively use the eep with wheat in light of foreign 
competition wasnt similar to a grain embargo 
yeutter said the concern was only about winter wheat eep will 
be available for the new crop of wheat he said 
yeutter also said there had been sensationalized journalism 
regarding some food safety issues 
rep jim jontz dind asked whether all corn should be tested 
for aflatoxin a carcinogen that shows up after a drought and has 
been widely reported by news organizations 
yeutter said there have been misconceptions about the extent of 
the aflatoxin problem and its danger testing of all corn would be 
costly he said 
we shouldnt change public policy because of sensationalized 
journalism he said 
jontz said the government should be responsive to consumers 
we ought to be responsive providing the consumer concerns are 
rational said yeutter 
the agriculture secretary voiced a similar opinion in a 
discussion with rep sid morrison rwash about the use of the 
growth and colorenhancing chemical alar on apple crops 
the health risk is miniscule yeutter said of way alar has 
been used on apple crops 
</TEXT>
